		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">Though there has been previous work aiming to design-out the theft of mobile phones, the nature of the crime is still evolving. For example, there is now evidence that expensive phones obtained free as part of subscription in the UK are being stolen for export and re-sale at high prices in overseas markets. There is therefore a need for a continually evolving and adapting response. This response is most efficient if it is a technological response incorporated into the design of phones to make them less attractive to thieves. This project will review the state of the art with respect to anti-theft devices used in phones and in other mobile data products where cross-fertilisation of prevention technologies may be appropriate. Based on this review, a set of concept designs will be developed. The concepts may incorporate design changes relating to specific aspects of product technology (such as dispersed technologies akin to those used for in-car stereos) as well as product iconography and semantics (the way it looks to consumers and the visual cues it gives to thieves regarding both its attractiveness and its in-built prevention capacity). These new concept designs will be markettested with a set of potential consumers (to check that the phones are still attractive to consumers) and with a set of offenders (to check the likely deterrent effects of the new designs). The interviews with offenders will be conducted in prisons in the East Midlands because these are geographically close to Loughborough University where the investigators are based. The findings of the interviews will be analysed, and the overall findings of the research reported in relevant journals for a crime prevention audience and a design/technology audience. While the main findings will be oriented towards the practical goal of crime prevention, we will also report upon the methodological aspects of using in-prison interviews to market-test the prevention potential of new crime-proof technological responses to crime.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
